<paragraph id="8BEF36A3FFE8FFC9A5F8FD631EEEFCA4" blockId="24.[136,1452,158,904]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE8FFC9A5F8FD631F19FD14" bold="true" box="[189,294,698,724]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Notes:—</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C504D20FFE8FFC9A463FD621FE8FD14" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" box="[294,471,698,724]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" genus="Petrea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="volubilis">
<emphasis id="B924EAB1FFE8FFC9A463FD621FE8FD14" box="[294,471,698,724]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Petrea volubilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has several synonyms, presenting great variation in the size of the leaves and flowers, and the 
<typeStatus id="54EB8801FFE8FFC9A5A1FD061F2BFD39" box="[228,276,735,761]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">type</typeStatus>
of indument (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE8FFC9A4F2FD071C7AFD38" author="Rueda, R. M." box="[439,581,734,760]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" pagination="610 - 652" refId="ref37895" refString="Rueda, R. M. (1994) Systematics and evolution of the genus Petrea (Verbenaceae). Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden 81: 610 - 652. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 2399914" type="journal article" year="1994">Rueda 1994</bibRefCitation>
). This species can be differentiated from the other 
<taxonomicName id="4C504D20FFE8FFC9A1CFFD071B28FD38" authorityName="J. Saint-Hilaire" authorityYear="1805" box="[1162,1303,734,760]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Verbenaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Verbenaceae</taxonomicName>
found in the 
<collectingRegion id="4994F841FFE8FFC9A5CDFCDB1F16FCDC" box="[136,297,770,796]" country="Brazil" name="Espirito Santo" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Espírito Santo</collectingRegion>
by the lianescent habit, leaves with apex mucronate; pedicellate flowers, and profoundly lobed calyx, purple or lilac, longer than the corolla. It is commonly cultivated in 
<collectingCountry id="F3477633FFE8FFC9A6C5FCFF1DFBFC80" box="[896,964,806,832]" name="Brazil" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Brazil</collectingCountry>
for ornamental purposes (
<bibRefCitation id="EFC14B52FFE8FFC9A1AFFCFF1EFBFCA4" author="Lorenzi, H. &amp; Souza, H. S." pageId="24" pageNumber="25" refId="ref35272" refString="Lorenzi, H. &amp; Souza, H. S. (2001) Plantas ornamentais do Brasil: arbustivas, herbaceas e trepadeiras. Instituto Plantarum, Nova Odessa, 1088 pp." type="book" year="2001">Lorenzi &amp; Souza 2001</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BEF36A3FFE8FFC9A5F8FCB71C37FC48" blockId="24.[136,1452,158,904]" box="[189,520,878,904]" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
